{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"0e0d1914-4a03-4a24-9f04-6fa4a9c30e0d","content":"# Using MCP Inspector with a C# stdio Server\n\nRun the MCP Inspector with `npx`:\n\n```bash\nnpx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./path/to/YourServer.csproj\n```\n\nThis launches a web UI (typically at `http://localhost:5173`) that connects to your server over stdio.\n\n**From the Inspector UI you can:**\n- Browse available tools, resources, and prompts\n- Invoke tools with custom inputs and see responses\n- View raw JSON-RPC messages for debugging\n\n**Tips:**\n- If your server needs arguments, append them: `npx @modelcontextprotocol/inspector dotnet run --project ./Server.csproj -- --arg1 value`\n- Set environment variables with `--env KEY=VALUE` before the command.\n- Use `--server-url` if you need to change the proxy port.\n\n**Debugging with breakpoints:** Launch your server separately with a debugger attached, then point the Inspector at it via a wrapper script that starts the already-running process's stdin/stdout — or simply use `DOTNET_ENVIRONMENT=Development` and log to stderr (Inspector displays stderr output in its console panel).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"7d431379-f76c-440f-bc8d-87c324543378","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking how to use the MCP Inspector to interactively test and debug their C# MCP server that uses stdio transport. This is a general knowledge question about tooling - I can answer this directly without needing to search the codebase.","outputTokens":343,"requestId":"C01C:244C23:1D06434:20A47AB:6A07C2D2"},"id":"a9941282-aea2-4458-9998-26546a31ac08","timestamp":"2026-05-16T01:05:33.046Z","parentId":"3ff8c2d6-8667-4830-9549-6219b4c4d47b"}
